column1: #Text=( Dutch Low Saxon : Nedersaksies , Dutch : Nedersaksisch ) is a group of West Low German , dialects spoken in the northeastern Netherlands .
#Text=It is assumed to be the native language of between 1 and 2 million people in the Netherlands .

#Text=Of course , Dutch Low Saxon is highly likely to be mutualy intelligible with Low German , however , as each language is influenced by respectively Dutch and High German , some misunderstandings are possible .
#Text=The class “ Dutch Low Saxon ” is not unanimous .

#Text=From a diachronic point of view , the Dutch Low Saxon dialects are merely the Low German dialects which are native to areas in the Netherlands ( as opposed to areas in northern Germany where Low German is the most common term accepted for these dialects ) .
#Text=From a strictly synchronic point of view , however , some linguists classify Dutch Low Saxon as a variety of Dutch .
#Text=Also , as a practical matter , Dutch Low Saxon is influenced by standard Dutch , whereas Low German in Germany is influenced by standard German .
#Text=Since Dutch Low Saxon , like its counterpart across the German border , is not a unified language , it is often hard to find two people speaking the same version of Dutch Low Saxon .
#Text=However , its clear resemblance to Dutch and the fact that most people in the Netherlands were taught the English , it wo n't be hard to be understood if you speak a poor Dutch Low Saxon .
#Text=Communication is more likely to be in Dutch or even English , however the locals would be impressed seeing a foreigner talking with them in their own dialect .
#Text=Writing system and dialect represented on this page
#Text=The writing system chosen to write Dutch Low Saxon is the Algemene Nedersaksiese Schriefwieze ( ANS ) developed in 2011 by the Wikipedia Community .
#Text=It was made in order to be able to then create a Dutch Low Saxon version of Wikipedia .
#Text=It is now considered a true , valid writing style for Dutch Low Saxon , used in other contexts a Wikipedia or internet .

#Text=The dialect proposed here is highly inspired by the Drenthe dialect ( Drèents ) , however , we tried to choose the most common forms to kind of represent a true image of the Dutch Low Saxon dialects .
#Text=Do n't forget however that it is not one single dialect , and that the sentences proposed on this page may be pronounced differently in some regions of the Netherlands .
#Text=Dutch Low Saxon has some vowel sounds that are not known in many other languages so they may be hard to learn .
#Text=a : like ' a ' in " calm " , ( but shorter )

column1: #Text=y : like ' i ' in " pin " or ' ee ' in " deep "
#Text=ä , ää : somewhat similar to ee , like ' a ' in " day " ( without pronouncing the ' y'-sound at the end )
#Text=e , ee : like ' a ' in " day " ( without pronouncing the ' y'-sound at the end )
#Text=ö , öö : similar to eu , like ' e ' in " mercy "
#Text=u , uu : like ' ü ' in German " München "
#Text=iew : like ' ea ' in " sea " , followed by a ' w'-sound
#Text=oa : like ' oa ' in goat , highly stressed
#Text=oai : like ' oa ' followed by a ' y'-sound
#Text=ooi : like ' oo ' followed by a ' y'-sound
#Text=ööi : like ' öö ' followed by a ' y'-sound
#Text=ui : like ' i ' in " sir " followed by a ' y'-sound , somewhat similar to ' ööi '
#Text=c : like ' c ' in " can " ( k ) or the ' c ' in " certain " ( s )

#Text=g : like ' g ' in " go " at the beginning of a word , within a word or at the end of it , ' g ' is pronounced either like a kind of ' ch'-sound in German Nacht ( a guttural sound similar to Spanish ' jotta'-sound )
#Text=n : like ' n ' in " no " ; often dropped at the end of words
#Text=r : similar to ' r ' in " row " but from the back of the throat , like the French ' r '
#Text=sch : usually like ' s ' followed by ' ch'-sound , especially after e , i , can also sound like ' sk ' in ' skip ' or like ' sh ' in ' ship '
#Text=ng : like both ' ng ' in " singing " , and ' ng ' in " finger " at the end of a word
#Text=How are you ? : Hoe geat et met di'j ? ( hoo GHAYT et mett day ? )
#Text=How are you ? ( informal ) : Hoe geat et ? ( hoo GHAYT et ? )
#Text=Fine , thank you . : Good , dank di'j . ( GOOT dahnk uu )
#Text=What is your name ? : Hoe heet ie ? ( hoo HAYT ee ? )
#Text=What is your name ? ( informal ) : Hoe heetst du ? ( hoo HAYT-st doo ? )
#Text=My name is ______ . : Mien naom is ______ . ( meen NOHM is _____ . )
#Text=Nice to meet you . : Aonenaom kennis te maoken .
